The paper involves probability theory and its applications in computer science, specifically in learning theory and pseudorandomness. The use of Gaussian distributions and polytopes suggests a connection to information theory (cs.IT) and computational geometry (cs.CG). The mention of agnostic learning algorithms and pseudorandom generators suggests a connection to machine learning (cs.LG) and complexity theory (cs.CC). Finally, the use of halfspaces and polytopes suggests a connection to discrete mathematics and combinatorial optimization (cs.DS).
